{
  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain Allama Iqbal's *Asrar-i-Khudi* (Secrets of the Self), his seminal Persian philosophical poem where the concept of *khudi* (often inadequately rendered as \"self\" or \"ego\") is most centrally developed and explored across numerous verses.** \n\nIqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* (in three parts) is present,[^1] [^2] [^3] and its descriptions reference themes of \"self-realization\" and \"individual empowerment,\" but searches of the English translations yield no direct discussions of *khudi*, verses contrasting it with English \"self,\" or passages where a literal \"self\" translation distorts meaning. \"Khudi\" appears only in transliterations of other Urdu poets like Ghalib and Zauq (often as \"be-khudi,\" implying self-loss), not Iqbal.[^4]\n\nWithout the key texts, I cannot identify a specific verse or explain *khudi*'s nuanced role (e.g., as dynamic self-affirmation rooted in divine creativity, beyond Western egoism) from the corpus.\n\n[^1]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Allama Iqbal (1924).\n[^2]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Allama Iqbal (1924).\n[^3]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Allama Iqbal (1924).\n[^4]: E.g., Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, various chapters.",
